:::summary
Sociology is the systematic study of human social life — examining how individuals are shaped by, and in turn shape, the groups, institutions, and structures in which they live. From the family and the congregation to the nation-state and the global economy, sociology investigates the invisible architecture of human community. The Christian tradition has its own rich account of social life rooted in covenant, creation, and the nature of the Church as the Body of Christ — an account that both enriches and critiques the findings of empirical sociology.
